    <div xml:id="PN393">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>patimutaṟ paḻakāp paḻaṅkaṇ vāḻkkaik</l>
<l>kuṟuneṭun tuṇaiyoṭu kūmai vītaliṟ</l>
<l>kuṭimuṟai pāṭi yoyyeṉa varunti</l>
<l>yaṭaṉacai maṟantaveṅ kuḻici malarkkum</l>
<l>kaṭaṉaṟi yāḷar piṟanāṭ ṭiṉmaiyiṉ</l>
<l>vaḷḷaṉ maiyiṉem varaivōr yāreṉa</l>
<l>vuḷḷiya vuḷḷamō ṭulainacai tuṇaiyā</l>
<l>...kavaka vellā morupāṟ paṭṭeṉa</l>
<l>malartā raṇṇaṉi ṉallicai yuḷḷi</l>
<l>yīrṅkai maṟantave ṉirumpē rokkal</l>
<l>kūrnta vevvamviṭak koḻuniṇaṅ kiḻippak</l>
<l>kōṭaip parutti vīṭuniṟai peyta</l>
<l>mūṭaip paṇṭa miṭainiṟain taṉṉa</l>
<l>veṇṇiṇa mūri yaruḷa nāḷuṟa</l>
<l>vīṉṟa varavi ṉāvuru kaṭukkumeṉ</l>
<l>ṟoṉṟupaṭu citāar tuvara nīkkip</l>
<l>pōtuviri pakaṉṟaip putumala raṉṉa</l>
<l>vakaṉṟumaṭi kaliṅka muṭīic celvamuṅ</l>
<l>kēṭiṉṟu nalkumati peruma māciṉ</l>
<l>matipurai mākkiṇai teḷirppa voṟṟi</l>
<l>yāṭumaka ḷalku loppa vāṭik</l>
<l>kōṭai yāyiṉuṅ kōṭi.............</l>
<l>kāviri purakku naṉṉāṭṭup poruna</l>
<l>vāyvāḷ vaḷavaṉ vāḻkeṉap</l>
<l>pīṭukeḻu nōṉṟāḷ pāṭukam palavē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>In the absence of other lands of men who know [their] duty (5)</l>
<l>who would make our pots bloom that have forgotten the longing to cook, (4)</l>
<l>suffering cruelly when singing in the order of hamlets/families, (3)</l>
<l>because of being destroyed by poverty(?) along with long and short companions, (2)</l>
<l>in a living in distress in unfamiliar places, (1)</l>
<l>as companion the longing for a fire place, with a heart that remembers, (7)</l>
<l>saying “who is there to keep us out of generosity?”, (6)</l>
<l>………….. because all happens in one place (8)</l>
<l>o majesty with a flower garland, while, remembering your fame, (9)</l>
<l>my very big kinfolk that had forgotten moist hands (10)</l>
<l>tear fat fat so that [their] abundant trouble lets go [of them], (11)</l>
<l>as days occur when we are graced with pieces of white fat (14) ?</l>
<l>that are like densely filled stores in a receptacle (13) ?</l>
<l>into which the west wind had poured a dwindling fullness of cotton, (12) ?</l>
<l>removing in pieces my old worn-out rags (16)</l>
<l>that resembled the tongues of birthing snakes, (15)</l>
<l>spreading out [and] putting on [me] a folded Kaliṅkam cloth (18)</l>
<l>that was like the new blossoms of the Pakaṉṟai that opens [its] buds, (17)</l>
<l>grant without loss, o great man. (19a-c)</l>
<l>Pressing, so that it sounds, [my] big Kiṇai drum like the flawless moon, (19d-20)</l>
<l>fading so as to equal the hips of dancing girls, (21) ?</l>
<l>even though there is west wind, a crore ………… (22)</l>
<l>o fighter of the good land that is guarded by the Kāviri, (23)</l>
<l>saying “may Vaḷavaṉ with an excellent sword live” (24)</l>
<l>on [your] sturdy feet that possess greatness we will sing many [songs]. (25)</l>
</lg>
